| iPhone Root Password Hacked in Three Days                          |
|   from the not-that-it-will-do-anybody-any-good dept.              |
|   posted by Zonk on Tuesday July 03, @13:02 (Security)             |
|   http://apple.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/07/03/1622212        |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]unPlugged-2.0 writes "An Australian developer blog writes that [1]the
iPhone root password has already been cracked. The story outlines the
procedure but doesn't give the actual password. According to the story:
'The information came from an an official Apple iPhone [2]restore image.
The archive contains two .dmg disk images: a password encrypted system
image and an unencrypted user image. By delving into the unencrypted
image inquisitive hackers were able to discover that all iPhones ship
with predefined passwords to the accounts 'mobile' and 'root', the last
of which being the name of the privileged administration account on UNIX
based systems.' Though interesting, it doesn't seem as though the
password is good for anything. The article theorizes it may be left over
from development work, or could have been included to create a 'false
trail' for hackers."

Discuss this story at:
    http://apple.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/07/03/1622212

Links:
    0. http://www.pramari.com/
    1. http://www.builderau.com.au/blogs/byteclub/viewblogpost.htm?p=339270810
    2. http://appldnld.apple.com.edgesuite.net/content.info.apple.com/iPhone/061-3538.20070629.B7vXa/iPhone1,1_1.0_1A543a_Restore.ipsw


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Credit Industry Opposes Anti-ID Theft Method                       |
|   from the frozen-out dept.                                        |
|   posted by kdawson on Tuesday July 03, @13:52 (Privacy)           |
|   http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/07/03/1734258          |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]athloi alerts us to an opinion piece running in USA Today on the
[1]backlash against an effective tool to fight identity theft. The big
three credit bureaus don't like the numerous state laws that have been
passed requiring them to give consumers a simple way to freeze their
credit. Watch for a push at the federal level to get a watered-down
statute that pre-empts state laws. "Lawmakers across the country — pushed
by consumer advocacy groups — ... have passed laws that allow consumers
to freeze their credit, a surefire way to prevent thieves from opening
new accounts or obtaining a mortgage in a consumer's name. Under a
freeze, a consumer cuts off all access to his credit report and score,
even his own. All lenders require that information, so no one can borrow
money in the consumer's name until he or she lifts the freeze. It's
simple, and it works. So, of course, it's under threat from the Consumer
Data Industry Association, which represents the Big Three credit bureaus.
They make millions gathering and selling consumer data. Freezes cut into
that business."

Discuss this story at:
    http://yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/07/03/1734258

Links:
    0. http://www.dionysius.com/
    1. http://www.usatoday.com/news/opinion/2007-07-02-oppose_N.htm?csp=34


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Windows Loses Ground With Developers                               |
|   from the rising-tide-lifts-all-penguins dept.                    |
|   posted by kdawson on Tuesday July 03, @14:41 (Microsoft)         |
|   http://developers.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/07/03/1816227   |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

An anonymous reader notes that InfoWorld is covering a survey of North
American developers that claims that Linux is gaining share as the
[0]number of developers targeting Windows fell 11 percent over the last
year. [1]Evans Data has been conducting these surveys of client, server,
and Web developers since 1998. Evans Data says that the arrival of
Windows Vista likely only kept the numbers from being even worse. The big
gainer wasn't developing for a Web platform, but rather for Linux and
"nontraditional client devices." Windows is still dominant, with 65% of
developers writing code for this platform. Linux stands at almost 12%, up
from 8% a year earlier. The article says that Evans Data collected
information on Mac and Unix development but did not include them in this
year's report.

Discuss this story at:
    http://developers.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/07/03/1816227

Links:
    0. http://www.infoworld.com/article/07/07/02/mswindows-share_1.html
    1. http://www.evansdata.com/n2/surveys/northamerican_toc_07_1.shtml


